t><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3899.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Art supplies aye?</span><hr size=1> Well for pens you could go with the<br><br>SAKURE PIGMA MICRON- This is a felt tip pen with a fine tip, like a sharpie only better and without the fumes. They come in fine lines to thick ones. Also pat's personal favorite.<br><br>Im not really familiar with the western type of nibs but if you like manga then I suggest you buy some supplies from <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.howtodrawmanga.com">www.howtodrawmanga.com</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> <br><br>I doubt any art suppliers have any copic markers or  neopiko markers, even though ive never used them id say go with copic ive seen great images done with them. Whatever you do dont buy some corny markers at the art suppliers and another tip.<br><br>When buying pencis:<br>If you are going to buy wooden pencils and are only looking for a certain hardness or softness then I suggest you DONT buy an 12 or 13 pack of different hardness pencils, those are pretty expensive. Instead look for racks with pencils which state different lead hardness or softness on the sides and may i suggest you pick out: HB- this is great for sketching, 2h-4h hell maybe even get all of them. Like in one of pat's mechanical drawings he state something about harders pencils with better detailing. My guess is that the pencils will run you 89 cents-1 dollars each which is fair. <br><br>Hope this helps and if you have any more questions just ask!  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/usuperrats.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Super Rats</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(7/10/02 6:46:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3899.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.happysoda.com/images/eboardavbp.jpg height=130 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Art supplies aye?</span><hr size=1> There is no such thing as THE RIGHT equipment, but here are some thoughts.  You can also find equipment suggestions in the tutorials section of the Polykarbon site.<br><br>PAPER: For roughs and sketches, I usually use regular photocopier paper...sketch paper seems like a waste of money to me (and sketch paper is often low quality).  For the price of a 100 sheet SKETCHbook, I could get 500 sheets of good photocopier paper.  I go through like ten sheets of paper to get an idea or pose down and to use sketch paper for that is ridiculous.  Photocopier paper is great for scribbles you plan on throwing away.  For serious and final drawing then I'll use more expensive paper, like Strathmore 400 series Drawing or Bristol.  <br><br>PENCILS: Just about anything will do, as long as it is comfortable, seriously.  Mechanical pencils are nice, convenient, and clean.  2H lead is good for your underdrawing and HB lead is fine for finished pencil lines.<br><br>ERASERS:  Get a white stick eraser (Mars, Pentel, and Sanford all make good white stick erasers) -- the best for eradicating lines and is better for your paper than a pink eraser or the eraser on the mechanical pencil.  People also suggest kneaded erasers.  I've never been a fan of the kneaded eraser.  I find that it leaves a residue on the paper that attracts dirt, but many people swear by kneaded erasers.  They're like 99 cents, so get one to see if you like it.<br><br>PENS:  Sakura Pigma Microns are a great way to start learning how to ink.  There are many of different tools, but Microns are an excellent place to start.  They come in different widths, but the 01, 03, 05, and 08 widths are what you should get if you don't want to buy them all...or even 005, 02, 05, 08 is a good setup, particularly if you draw small or have a lot of details, the 005 is great.<br><br>OTHER THING: One thing I would get is a draftsman's brush to clear away eraser debris from your paper.  Using your hand to clear off junk can smudge up a picture fairly quickly.  You can usually find these things by the drafting supplies, where you'll find the rulers, T-squares, french curves, etc. <p>=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=<br>If you ever want me to grope your chest, let me know.  It's better than letting that spider eat you up inside, don't you think?.<br><br><a href="http://www.happysoda.com"><img src="http://www.happysoda.com/banner.gif" border="1"></A></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showPrevMessage?topicID=3899.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showNextMessage?topicID=3899.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3899.topic&index=2><img src=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/addreply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.emailToFriend?topicID=3899.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.threadControl?topicID=3899.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/professional/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands (Moderator only)</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=3899.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.unsubscribeUnregi